text: Imagine a kitchen where your countertop is not just a surface but also a fully functional cooking station—with no visible burners or clutter. You place your cookware directly on the countertop, and within seconds, it heats up, allowing you to cook just as you would on a traditional stove. When you lift the cookware and touch the same spot, the surface remains cool, completely safe to the touch. No residual heat, no risk of burns—just a seamless, modern cooking experience. This is the power of Invisacook, an advanced invisible induction cooktop installed beneath the countertop. Using magnetic induction technology, it transfers heat directly to the cookware while keeping the countertop itself unaffected. This means you can cook, move your pots and pans freely, and still use your countertop as a regular workspace when you're done—no bulky appliances, no wasted space. Beyond just functionality, Invisacook redefines kitchen design by offering a sleek, minimalist aesthetic that blends innovation with luxury. text: Our relationship and marriage have been far from picture perfect. I keep seeing posts saying “if marriage is hard, you probably married the wrong person” but I don’t believe that’s true. Especially not for the believer. I’ll always believe that kingdom-enhancing marriages are one of the enemy’s number one targets. If your marriage has the power to reflect Christ’s love, to serve others, to raise disciples, of course it’ll face attack. Marriage is meant to be sanctifying. It’s meant to make us holy, not just happy. Do I believe God desires harmony in marriage? Absolutely. But Garrett and I started dating at 18… and we were messy, messy humans. We still are. Now we’re just messy humans who’ve walked with Jesus seven years longer. Messy humans who’ve been discipled, who’ve met the Holy Spirit, who’ve gone to counseling, who’ve grown and matured and learned how to love more selflessly and sacrificially. Our marriage was never meant to be the source of our fulfillment. Garrett’s job isn’t to fill my soul. Should he pursue my heart? Yes. But should I depend on him to complete me? Absolutely not. And vice versa. It’s not my job to complete Garrett either. We’ve screamed. We’ve fought. We even had the cops called on us in the first three months of marriage because of how loud we were arguing. Not proud, just keeping it real. But the Lord has called us into union, and He’s faithful to finish what He started. So to the young married couple stuck in the trenches, figuring each other out while also figuring yourself out, your marriage isn’t broken. You didn’t choose wrong. God didn’t mess up. Keep seeking the cross. Die to yourself. Admit when you’re wrong. Invite community in. Get the help you need. Pray for your spouse more than you complain about them to your friends. Pray for your spouse more than you nag them. Test God on it. Pray, pray, pray fervently for your spouse and your marriage. Watch Him move. And please hear me. This does not apply to abusive relationships, mentally or physically. That is not okay. Get help. Your safety matters.  #momsoftiktok #christiantiktok #christianity #christiangirl #christiantok #christianrelationships #followingjesus #marriage #marriedyoung #marriedlife #marriagegoals #couplestiktok

Field Notes – Entry #210 Location: Edge of the ornamental pond, Marrow Gardens, late afternoon after rain Species: Rosarachne praenobilis I spotted it poised atop a single slender stem, a striking sight even among the lush border plantings. At first glance it appeared to be an elaborate blossom: wide lavender petals opening outward, crowned by a dense, tightly furled rosebud at the center. Only on closer inspection did the deception reveal itself—the outer petals were genuine enough, but peeking just beneath the central bloom were thin, jointed legs, delicate and crablike, anchoring the creature to its perch. The central rosebud quivered, then pulsed. In a strange, swift sequence, the petals pulled inward, wrapping the heart of the flower tight again, as though bracing against some invisible threat. Just as suddenly, it unfurled—this time wider, more triumphant, the deeper pink core bursting open in layered spirals of silken petal. Somewhere hidden within, beneath the folds of the bloom, the creature’s true head remained unseen—sheathed inside its living disguise. The limbs never retreated, remaining visible under the opened flower, subtle and alert. Among the local horticulturists, Rosarachne praenobilis is known as “the Keeper’s Bloom.” An old story claims these creatures once guarded sacred ponds, ensuring only the deserving could reach the waters. Watching it now, perfectly balanced between stillness and bloom, it is not hard to believe. . text: We tried Lulu because her seller told me she had a pony that might be a good fit for Teagan, but she didn’t have a finished lead change. That’s all we knew before we met her.  We showed up not knowing what the pony looked like, whether it was a mare or gelding, its age, or anything else. But when Taegan got on, she was more relaxed than she had been on a pony in a while. She wasn’t her favorite pony we tried, but every one of my friends who watched the videos that day said she just looked so comfortable.  They did a few jumps, just in a warmup ring, and off the right lead they disagreed on a distance… not once, not twice… but 3 times! What did Lulu do? She kept saying “that’s okay, we can do it kid!” And went over every time.  Taegan is 7. She is going to make many mistakes as she learns. Not every small pony will jump your kid out of a sticky situation at a 2’3” oxer, but this one will, and we are so lucky she’s ours.

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Lebron isn’t just a man. He’s a phenomenon. He’s a celestial event, a once-in-a-lifetime alignment of the stars, a cosmic masterpiece sculpted by the basketball gods themselves. When he moves, it’s not just movement—it’s poetry. Every dribble, every pass, every dunk, every single bead of sweat that glistens under the arena lights is like a love letter sent directly to my heart. How could one human being be so perfect? It defies all logic, all reason, all earthly explanations. His voice? It’s like a lullaby and a war cry wrapped into one. When he speaks, it’s as if the universe itself pauses just to listen. The way he commands respect, the way he leads, the way he exists—it does something to me. When I see him laugh, when I see that perfect, radiant, joy-filled smile, I swear my soul leaves my body. I float above the world, untethered by gravity, held aloft only by the sheer force of my adoration for this man. And then there’s his physique—his godlike, sculpted-by-the-heavens physique. Every muscle, every vein, every perfectly chiseled inch of him is a testament to human perfection. He is not just a man, he is an ideal, a dream given flesh, the pinnacle of what the human form can achieve. The way he moves, with such grace and power, is enough to leave me breathless. He is a masterpiece in motion, a living, breathing work of art. But it’s not just the physical. Oh no. My love for LeBron transcends the physical realm. It’s the mind, the heart, the soul. The intelligence, the vision, the leadership, the wisdom. LeBron doesn’t just play basketball—he orchestrates it. He is the conductor of a beautiful, chaotic symphony, and every game he plays is another masterpiece added to his collection. His IQ, both on and off the court, is unmatched. The way he reads the game, the way he sees things before they happen, the way he adapts, evolves, dominates—it leaves me in a constant state of awe. And let’s talk about his heart. text: Field Notes – Entry #210 Location: Edge of the ornamental pond, Marrow Gardens, late afternoon after rain Species: Rosarachne praenobilis I spotted it poised atop a single slender stem, a striking sight even among the lush border plantings. At first glance it appeared to be an elaborate blossom: wide lavender petals opening outward, crowned by a dense, tightly furled rosebud at the center. Only on closer inspection did the deception reveal itself—the outer petals were genuine enough, but peeking just beneath the central bloom were thin, jointed legs, delicate and crablike, anchoring the creature to its perch. The central rosebud quivered, then pulsed. In a strange, swift sequence, the petals pulled inward, wrapping the heart of the flower tight again, as though bracing against some invisible threat. Just as suddenly, it unfurled—this time wider, more triumphant, the deeper pink core bursting open in layered spirals of silken petal. Somewhere hidden within, beneath the folds of the bloom, the creature’s true head remained unseen—sheathed inside its living disguise. The limbs never retreated, remaining visible under the opened flower, subtle and alert. Among the local horticulturists, Rosarachne praenobilis is known as “the Keeper’s Bloom.” An old story claims these creatures once guarded sacred ponds, ensuring only the deserving could reach the waters. Watching it now, perfectly balanced between stillness and bloom, it is not hard to believe. . text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: “I’m not a zoomer-arounder like you…” The truth comes out. Some days, you just want to lay around all day. I get it. Life with a zoomer-arounder mama and papa can be tough!  Truth is, Emi is a bit of a zoomer too—but she knows when she needs her downtime. Like me, she needs that balance of also being a ‘layer-arounder.’ I’m glad she can tell me when she feels that way and knows I’ll support her.✨ This conversation went on for at least 5 more minutes as Emi and I skied together last spring. I listened, following up on her thoughts to better understand what she was expressing and feeling. I learned a lot. She revealed that if she has her way, she’d snuggle with her Squishmallows all day, only getting up to brush her teeth—so, there’s that. But I sensed there was more to it knowing she’s the kiddo usually begging to go skiing or sprint down the trail in a hike. ⬇️ This was newly-5-year-old Emi’s first time skiing off the very top of Mount Bachelor. It was steep, the snow was firm, and I could hear the hesitation in her voice. So, we took a break right after this exchange. I realized she was too hot, so I peeled off one of her layers, reminded her, “I got you,” and told her I had the slope rope to connect us if she wanted it. Once we made it past the steep section, hit some softer snow, and ate some gummies, she zoomed off ahead of me, and I couldn’t keep up!  As ski season arrives, it’s a good reminder for us parents to check in with the deeper story to what’s going on when we’re out on the mountain with our kids.  @Milo @Stio Outdoor Apparel @mt.bachelor @Reima @ikonpass  #winteriscoming #zoomerarounder #skiingwithkids #girlswhoski #skigirl #outdoormom

text: Imagine a kitchen where your countertop is not just a surface but also a fully functional cooking station—with no visible burners or clutter. You place your cookware directly on the countertop, and within seconds, it heats up, allowing you to cook just as you would on a traditional stove. When you lift the cookware and touch the same spot, the surface remains cool, completely safe to the touch. No residual heat, no risk of burns—just a seamless, modern cooking experience. This is the power of Invisacook, an advanced invisible induction cooktop installed beneath the countertop. Using magnetic induction technology, it transfers heat directly to the cookware while keeping the countertop itself unaffected. This means you can cook, move your pots and pans freely, and still use your countertop as a regular workspace when you're done—no bulky appliances, no wasted space. Beyond just functionality, Invisacook redefines kitchen design by offering a sleek, minimalist aesthetic that blends innovation with luxury. text: Field Notes – Entry #210 Location: Edge of the ornamental pond, Marrow Gardens, late afternoon after rain Species: Rosarachne praenobilis I spotted it poised atop a single slender stem, a striking sight even among the lush border plantings. At first glance it appeared to be an elaborate blossom: wide lavender petals opening outward, crowned by a dense, tightly furled rosebud at the center. Only on closer inspection did the deception reveal itself—the outer petals were genuine enough, but peeking just beneath the central bloom were thin, jointed legs, delicate and crablike, anchoring the creature to its perch. The central rosebud quivered, then pulsed. In a strange, swift sequence, the petals pulled inward, wrapping the heart of the flower tight again, as though bracing against some invisible threat. Just as suddenly, it unfurled—this time wider, more triumphant, the deeper pink core bursting open in layered spirals of silken petal. Somewhere hidden within, beneath the folds of the bloom, the creature’s true head remained unseen—sheathed inside its living disguise. The limbs never retreated, remaining visible under the opened flower, subtle and alert. Among the local horticulturists, Rosarachne praenobilis is known as “the Keeper’s Bloom.” An old story claims these creatures once guarded sacred ponds, ensuring only the deserving could reach the waters. Watching it now, perfectly balanced between stillness and bloom, it is not hard to believe. . text: Our relationship and marriage have been far from picture perfect. I keep seeing posts saying “if marriage is hard, you probably married the wrong person” but I don’t believe that’s true. Especially not for the believer. I’ll always believe that kingdom-enhancing marriages are one of the enemy’s number one targets. If your marriage has the power to reflect Christ’s love, to serve others, to raise disciples, of course it’ll face attack. Marriage is meant to be sanctifying. It’s meant to make us holy, not just happy. Do I believe God desires harmony in marriage? Absolutely. But Garrett and I started dating at 18… and we were messy, messy humans. We still are. Now we’re just messy humans who’ve walked with Jesus seven years longer. Messy humans who’ve been discipled, who’ve met the Holy Spirit, who’ve gone to counseling, who’ve grown and matured and learned how to love more selflessly and sacrificially. Our marriage was never meant to be the source of our fulfillment. Garrett’s job isn’t to fill my soul. Should he pursue my heart? Yes. But should I depend on him to complete me? Absolutely not. And vice versa. It’s not my job to complete Garrett either. We’ve screamed. We’ve fought. We even had the cops called on us in the first three months of marriage because of how loud we were arguing. Not proud, just keeping it real. But the Lord has called us into union, and He’s faithful to finish what He started. So to the young married couple stuck in the trenches, figuring each other out while also figuring yourself out, your marriage isn’t broken. You didn’t choose wrong. God didn’t mess up. Keep seeking the cross. Die to yourself. Admit when you’re wrong. Invite community in. Get the help you need. Pray for your spouse more than you complain about them to your friends. Pray for your spouse more than you nag them. Test God on it. Pray, pray, pray fervently for your spouse and your marriage. Watch Him move. And please hear me. This does not apply to abusive relationships, mentally or physically. That is not okay. Get help. Your safety matters.  #momsoftiktok #christiantiktok #christianity #christiangirl #christiantok #christianrelationships #followingjesus #marriage #marriedyoung #marriedlife #marriagegoals #couplestiktok

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: A perfect beach day for Buster☀️ For those that don’t know his story, Buster is an 11.5 year old hospice bernese mountain dog that I adopted from @Tusc. Co. Humane Society a little over a week ago. Unfortunately, Buster has never been cared for like he deserved.  I took him in to my incredible vet, @Snodgrass Vet and we did bloodwork, xrays, and an ultrasound to see where we were at health wise. We found that Buster has tumors on his heart and spleen, most likely hemangiosarcoma, and he was severely anemic as a result. This type of cancer is highly malignant and aggressive. Buster received a blood transfusion and was hooked up to fluids most of the day before coming home. At that point, we weren’t sure he’d make it through the holiday weekend, but he did, and he’s not giving up yet ❤️‍ Overall, he’s doing really well! He is a VERY happy boy and doesn’t seem to be uncomfortable or in any pain at all.  Getting him to eat is no easy task. He’s very picky— if he likes something one morning, he’ll probably turn his nose to it by that afternoon. He’s refusing most dog foods, but if he decides he’ll eat some dog food, his favorite has been different flavors of @Open Farm Pet freeze dried morsels. He’s still eating an assortment of human foods— steak, salmon, lean beef, pork chops, chicken, deli meat, and of course, goldfish crackers. Whatever he chooses to eat, he likes it cut into tiny pieces, and he wants it to be hand fed to him. He won’t eat it if it’s put on a plate or in a bowl… he just tries to bury the plate or bowl if so.  Ultimately, Buster doesn’t have much time left— we just don’t know if that is days or weeks, or by miracle, a month or two, but rather than counting down the days, we are trying to make every day count. Buster deserves to know what the good life is all about, so we are going to make the most of whatever time we are blessed with. He is truly the best boy and I’m so glad we get to spoil him for the rest of his life, however long it may be.  Be sure to follow us if you want to watch this sweet old man finally experience the love and care he’s always deserved in his final chapter ❤️ #bernesemountaindog #rescuedog

I decided to double up on reel meals since I’m behind with editing… Loaded Chicken Twice Baked Potato!!! Nuff said. I wish y’all could taste through the screen omg. I tore this meal DOWN ——————————————— RECIPEEEE! If y'all been following me y'all know I do not measure but i'll try my best.  Ingredients:  - Russet Potatoes  - Heavy Cream - Colby Jack Cheese - Seasonings for taste (in step list)  - Sharp Cheddar Cheese  - Unsalted Butter  - Vegetable Oil - Broccoli (optional for filling) - Aluminum Foil - Garlic Paste  - Sour Cream - EVOO - Cubed Chicken (cut up breasts or tenderloin)  [Baked Potato] * 1st you want to prep your potatoes. You're basically making a baked potato. Take your potatoes (russet) and wash them. Then cover with oil (I used vegetable oil) and individually wrap each potato tightly in aluminum foil. Bake in the oven at 400 degrees F for about an hour. * Once potatoes are soft and cooked completely remove the foil and cut down the middle of each potato, hot dog style. Scoop out the inside of the potato and put into an empty mixing bowl. To the mixing bowl you're going to add 1 stick of unsalted melted butter, tbsp of garlic paste, parsley, 1 tsp onion powder, 1 tsp garlic salt, cooked broccoli, 1/2c grated sharp cheddar cheese, pepper, and 2 tbsp sour cream. Mix together and scoop filling back into potatoes. [Sauce]  * Add 1 tbsp butter to pan, 1 tsp garlic paste and parsley and melt down. Add about 1cup of heavy cream and let cook for 5 minutes to thicken. Add pepper, onion powder and lawrys seasoning salt to season. Add colby jack cheese (about 1cup) and mix until sauce is thick and consistency you like. [Chicken]  * I used chicken beasts and cut into cubes. Add EVOO and seasoned with parsley, onion powder, garlic powder and adobo. Cooked in a greased pan until done. * Add thin layer of sauce on potatoes, then chicken, then sauce again and finally top with more cheese and bake on 125 until cheese is melted. #loadedpotato #twicebakedpotato #chickenloadedpotato #cookingtiktok #chefd #fivestarmeals #dinnerideas #dinnerinspo

text: Imagine a kitchen where your countertop is not just a surface but also a fully functional cooking station—with no visible burners or clutter. You place your cookware directly on the countertop, and within seconds, it heats up, allowing you to cook just as you would on a traditional stove. When you lift the cookware and touch the same spot, the surface remains cool, completely safe to the touch. No residual heat, no risk of burns—just a seamless, modern cooking experience. This is the power of Invisacook, an advanced invisible induction cooktop installed beneath the countertop. Using magnetic induction technology, it transfers heat directly to the cookware while keeping the countertop itself unaffected. This means you can cook, move your pots and pans freely, and still use your countertop as a regular workspace when you're done—no bulky appliances, no wasted space. Beyond just functionality, Invisacook redefines kitchen design by offering a sleek, minimalist aesthetic that blends innovation with luxury. text: Field Notes – Entry #210 Location: Edge of the ornamental pond, Marrow Gardens, late afternoon after rain Species: Rosarachne praenobilis I spotted it poised atop a single slender stem, a striking sight even among the lush border plantings. At first glance it appeared to be an elaborate blossom: wide lavender petals opening outward, crowned by a dense, tightly furled rosebud at the center. Only on closer inspection did the deception reveal itself—the outer petals were genuine enough, but peeking just beneath the central bloom were thin, jointed legs, delicate and crablike, anchoring the creature to its perch. The central rosebud quivered, then pulsed. In a strange, swift sequence, the petals pulled inward, wrapping the heart of the flower tight again, as though bracing against some invisible threat. Just as suddenly, it unfurled—this time wider, more triumphant, the deeper pink core bursting open in layered spirals of silken petal. Somewhere hidden within, beneath the folds of the bloom, the creature’s true head remained unseen—sheathed inside its living disguise. The limbs never retreated, remaining visible under the opened flower, subtle and alert. Among the local horticulturists, Rosarachne praenobilis is known as “the Keeper’s Bloom.” An old story claims these creatures once guarded sacred ponds, ensuring only the deserving could reach the waters. Watching it now, perfectly balanced between stillness and bloom, it is not hard to believe. . text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: “I’m not a zoomer-arounder like you…” The truth comes out. Some days, you just want to lay around all day. I get it. Life with a zoomer-arounder mama and papa can be tough!  Truth is, Emi is a bit of a zoomer too—but she knows when she needs her downtime. Like me, she needs that balance of also being a ‘layer-arounder.’ I’m glad she can tell me when she feels that way and knows I’ll support her.✨ This conversation went on for at least 5 more minutes as Emi and I skied together last spring. I listened, following up on her thoughts to better understand what she was expressing and feeling. I learned a lot. She revealed that if she has her way, she’d snuggle with her Squishmallows all day, only getting up to brush her teeth—so, there’s that. But I sensed there was more to it knowing she’s the kiddo usually begging to go skiing or sprint down the trail in a hike. ⬇️ This was newly-5-year-old Emi’s first time skiing off the very top of Mount Bachelor. It was steep, the snow was firm, and I could hear the hesitation in her voice. So, we took a break right after this exchange. text: HOW THE HELL DID THAT HAPPEN?! ⬇️ It looks a lot worse than it actually is, but my first freediving competiton wasn't without a bit of drama! After getting food poisoning the night before, I showed up to competiton still wanting to do a big performance.  I'd been doing regular 6+ minute static breath holds in training, but I didn't expect sickness and competition nerves to have such an effect ‍♂️ At the 5 minute 30 seconds mark, I completely lost my memory from low oxygen levels in my brain. When I surfaced at 5 minutes and 52 seconds, my oxygen levels were so low that my body started spasming involuntarily, otherwise known as a Loss Of Motor Control (LMC). Thankfully my coach @junglefreediver was there to yell at me and remind me to breathe. The next thing I remember was the judge removing my noseclip and me signalling that I was okay.  This was a good lesson that freediving when you're sick isn't a great idea, and to never dive alone!   @fred_petat #freediving #freediverlife #holdyourbreath #justbreathe #blackout #athlete #AIDA #aidainternational #merman #breathe #graphic #graphiccontent #underwater #freedivecompetition #competition #sport #freediver #breathhold #athletelife

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: “I’m not a zoomer-arounder like you…” The truth comes out. Some days, you just want to lay around all day. I get it. Life with a zoomer-arounder mama and papa can be tough! Like me, she needs that balance of also being a ‘layer-arounder.’ I’m glad she can tell me when she feels that way and knows I’ll support her.✨ This conversation went on for at least 5 more minutes as Emi and I skied together last spring. I listened, following up on her thoughts to better understand what she was expressing and feeling. I learned a lot. She revealed that if she has her way, she’d snuggle with her Squishmallows all day, only getting up to brush her teeth—so, there’s that. But I sensed there was more to it knowing she’s the kiddo usually begging to go skiing or sprint down the trail in a hike. ⬇️ This was newly-5-year-old Emi’s first time skiing off the very top of Mount Bachelor. It was steep, the snow was firm, and I could hear the hesitation in her voice. So, we took a break right after this exchange. I realized she was too hot, so I peeled off one of her layers, reminded her, “I got you,” and told her I had the slope rope to connect us if she wanted it. text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: “I’m not a zoomer-arounder like you…” The truth comes out. Some days, you just want to lay around all day. I get it. Life with a zoomer-arounder mama and papa can be tough!  Truth is, Emi is a bit of a zoomer too—but she knows when she needs her downtime. Like me, she needs that balance of also being a ‘layer-arounder.’ I’m glad she can tell me when she feels that way and knows I’ll support her.✨ This conversation went on for at least 5 more minutes as Emi and I skied together last spring. I listened, following up on her thoughts to better understand what she was expressing and feeling. I learned a lot. She revealed that if she has her way, she’d snuggle with her Squishmallows all day, only getting up to brush her teeth—so, there’s that. But I sensed there was more to it knowing she’s the kiddo usually begging to go skiing or sprint down the trail in a hike. ⬇️ This was newly-5-year-old Emi’s first time skiing off the very top of Mount Bachelor. It was steep, the snow was firm, and I could hear the hesitation in her voice. So, we took a break right after this exchange. I realized she was too hot, so I peeled off one of her layers, reminded her, “I got you,” and told her I had the slope rope to connect us if she wanted it. Once we made it past the steep section, hit some softer snow, and ate some gummies, she zoomed off ahead of me, and I couldn’t keep up!  As ski season arrives, it’s a good reminder for us parents to check in with the deeper story to what’s going on when we’re out on the mountain with our kids.  @Milo @Stio Outdoor Apparel @mt.bachelor @Reima @ikonpass  #winteriscoming #zoomerarounder #skiingwithkids #girlswhoski #skigirl #outdoormom

text: I can’t believe it has been FIVE whole years since I lost my daughter. I did not believe I would make it this far. I heavily dealt with anger, guilt, loneliness, depression, and anxiety these entire five years…and I am still dealing with them. The pain hurts way less than it did when it first happened, but I am still in pain. I am still mourning what I lost. I am still angry that she was stolen from me. I am angry that I do not have my 5 year old here with me. I am angry that I did not get to play with her in the Atlanta snow. I am angry that I can’t send her off to kindergarten this August. I am angry that I let fear control me. I remember being in the hospital room when they said she no longer had a heartbeat. I remember how heavy she felt from the wires and how swollen her face was from the medication. I remember the hospital chaplain praying over me as I screamed and cried my lungs out. I remember looking all over her body and seeing the marks from the autopsy. If I had a Time Machine I would tell someone how my sperm donor treated me. How he talked to me and how talked about the child that we shared. I knew I had to get my child and I away from this bastard but I did not just drop my shit and go. I wanted to leave on a good peaceful note but there was no peace with evil. I still don’t know what exactly happened and how he actually killed her. But who would want to know that anyways? I have enough images in my head. I just wish there was someway and somehow for my baby to still be here. She was wanted by her mother, her aunts and uncles, her grandmothers, grandfathers, cousins, and many loved ones. One day we will meet again. text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: “I’m not a zoomer-arounder like you…” The truth comes out. Some days, you just want to lay around all day. I get it. Life with a zoomer-arounder mama and papa can be tough!  Truth is, Emi is a bit of a zoomer too—but she knows when she needs her downtime. Like me, she needs that balance of also being a ‘layer-arounder.’ I’m glad she can tell me when she feels that way and knows I’ll support her.✨ This conversation went on for at least 5 more minutes as Emi and I skied together last spring. I listened, following up on her thoughts to better understand what she was expressing and feeling. I learned a lot. She revealed that if she has her way, she’d snuggle with her Squishmallows all day, only getting up to brush her teeth—so, there’s that. But I sensed there was more to it knowing she’s the kiddo usually begging to go skiing or sprint down the trail in a hike. ⬇️ This was newly-5-year-old Emi’s first time skiing off the very top of Mount Bachelor. It was steep, the snow was firm, and I could hear the hesitation in her voice. So, we took a break right after this exchange. I realized she was too hot, so I peeled off one of her layers, reminded her, “I got you,” and told her I had the slope rope to connect us if she wanted it. Once we made it past the steep section, hit some softer snow, and ate some gummies, she zoomed off ahead of me, and I couldn’t keep up!  As ski season arrives, it’s a good reminder for us parents to check in with the deeper story to what’s going on when we’re out on the mountain with our kids.  @Milo @Stio Outdoor Apparel @mt.bachelor @Reima @ikonpass  #winteriscoming #zoomerarounder #skiingwithkids #girlswhoski #skigirl #outdoormom

So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. text: “I’m not a zoomer-arounder like you…” The truth comes out. Some days, you just want to lay around all day. I get it. Life with a zoomer-arounder mama and papa can be tough!  Truth is, Emi is a bit of a zoomer too—but she knows when she needs her downtime. Like me, she needs that balance of also being a ‘layer-arounder.’ I’m glad she can tell me when she feels that way and knows I’ll support her.✨ This conversation went on for at least 5 more minutes as Emi and I skied together last spring. I listened, following up on her thoughts to better understand what she was expressing and feeling. I learned a lot. She revealed that if she has her way, she’d snuggle with her Squishmallows all day, only getting up to brush her teeth—so, there’s that. But I sensed there was more to it knowing she’s the kiddo usually begging to go skiing or sprint down the trail in a hike. ⬇️ This was newly-5-year-old Emi’s first time skiing off the very top of Mount Bachelor. It was steep, the snow was firm, and I could hear the hesitation in her voice. So, we took a break right after this exchange. I realized she was too hot, so I peeled off one of her layers, reminded her, “I got you,” and told her I had the slope rope to connect us if she wanted it. Once we made it past the steep section, hit some softer snow, and ate some gummies, she zoomed off ahead of me, and I couldn’t keep up! text: He lost his wife and 8-year-old child in the crash. He was the only one who survived. But Jerry Tuazon spoke with so much peace. He said, “Pinahiram lang sila ng Diyos. Sa amin, natutulog lang sila. Napatawad ko na ang driver.” He didn’t demand revenge. He didn’t blame the company. Instead, he asked people not to shut down Solid North. He said the drivers have families too. And people still need them. Jerry is a Seventh-Day Adventist. He was on his way to a church event when the crash happened. Even in deep pain, he showed compassion. Even after losing everything, he chose to think of others. He didn’t just survive. He lived with a kind of heart that most of us can only hope to have. This is not weakness. This is strength. This is faith. He is proof that God can turn tragedy into testimony. #fyp

text: HBO's 'The Pitt' star Supriya Ganesh has come out as queer! In an interview with Variety, the actor opened up about using she/they pronouns and how they were influenced by Lily Gladstone to come out. They said:  "That was a decision I think I made about a year and a half ago, actually influenced by Lily Gladstone in her decision to adopt she/they pronouns in acknowledgement of third-spirit people and some two-spirit people, I think that was a moment where I felt really seen, where I was like, “Oh, yeah, I don’t need to fit into this.” "Even though I feel like I identify a lot more with femininity, that doesn’t mean I always fit into what is a very Western idea of it. So I think that was why I made that decision. It also feels like a little bit of a shout-out, being like, “Hey, I’m queer. See me.” I feel like sometimes I pass really well. I also want queer brown women to look at me and know that that’s someone they can turn to and relate to." The Pitt is a medical drama on HBO in which Ganesh stars as Dr. Samira Mohan. #thepitt #hbomax #comingout #supriyaganesh #genderfluid #queertiktok

This is the traditional gua sha I grew up with—it’s ancient Chinese treatment, and yes, I know it’s gotten popular lately in the beauty world, but this is the gua sha I know!  It may look a little intense, but I promise it doesn’t hurt and the relief is instant. It’s incredible for easing tension, stress, and seasonal colds.  Usually, someone else does it for you, but since I don’t have anyone nearby who knows how, I’ve been doing it myself for years. Every few months, or whenever I’m feeling extra stressed or like I’m coming down with something, gua sha makes me feel totally reset. Honestly, I’ve been hesitant to share this since it can look kind of intimidating, but this practice means a lot to me. It reminds me of my aunt—the amazing woman who raised me and taught me how to do this as a kid. text: Imagine a kitchen where your countertop is not just a surface but also a fully functional cooking station—with no visible burners or clutter. You place your cookware directly on the countertop, and within seconds, it heats up, allowing you to cook just as you would on a traditional stove. When you lift the cookware and touch the same spot, the surface remains cool, completely safe to the touch. No residual heat, no risk of burns—just a seamless, modern cooking experience. This is the power of Invisacook, an advanced invisible induction cooktop installed beneath the countertop. Using magnetic induction technology, it transfers heat directly to the cookware while keeping the countertop itself unaffected. This means you can cook, move your pots and pans freely, and still use your countertop as a regular workspace when you're done—no bulky appliances, no wasted space. Beyond just functionality, Invisacook redefines kitchen design by offering a sleek, minimalist aesthetic that blends innovation with luxury. text: Field Notes – Entry #210 Location: Edge of the ornamental pond, Marrow Gardens, late afternoon after rain Species: Rosarachne praenobilis I spotted it poised atop a single slender stem, a striking sight even among the lush border plantings. At first glance it appeared to be an elaborate blossom: wide lavender petals opening outward, crowned by a dense, tightly furled rosebud at the center. Only on closer inspection did the deception reveal itself—the outer petals were genuine enough, but peeking just beneath the central bloom were thin, jointed legs, delicate and crablike, anchoring the creature to its perch. The central rosebud quivered, then pulsed. In a strange, swift sequence, the petals pulled inward, wrapping the heart of the flower tight again, as though bracing against some invisible threat. Just as suddenly, it unfurled—this time wider, more triumphant, the deeper pink core bursting open in layered spirals of silken petal. Somewhere hidden within, beneath the folds of the bloom, the creature’s true head remained unseen—sheathed inside its living disguise. The limbs never retreated, remaining visible under the opened flower, subtle and alert. Among the local horticulturists, Rosarachne praenobilis is known as “the Keeper’s Bloom.” An old story claims these creatures once guarded sacred ponds, ensuring only the deserving could reach the waters. Watching it now, perfectly balanced between stillness and bloom, it is not hard to believe. . text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: I went on a last-minute trip to Saint Helena Catholic Church in Louisiana and to Our Lady of Hope Catholic Retreat Center in Mississippi. It must have been quite an experience.  I know that Fr. Mark Beard has followers from all over the world who, like myself, never got to meet him, yet we love and miss him. I will be sharing more pictures and videos of Saint Helena Catholic Church, his gravesite, and Our Lady of Hope Catholic Retreat Center.  Eternal rest grant unto his soul O Lord. text: So we discovered several years ago that Abbey is a gestalt language processor. This means she speaks in associations and memories before words. This is a core part of her expressive language and why she’s often misunderstood and struggles. Memories and categories pop in her head before language does -before actual words. This can take her out of the moment and be very divisive in social situations. We’re still working on helping her understand that some of her memories and categories cause confusion to the outside world. By discussing it here, we hope that she may be able to translate for us so we have a better understanding of what she really means. Because she is often misunderstood.  Please understand that I am aware I am leading this conversation because I’m helping her get to the core of the memory and category versus what she’s really trying to say. There is a disconnect between those two things and by modeling and discussing with her, this helps her bridge those two things - she cannot do this on her own yet but she understands this is the way her mind works. @Ab@Abbeyb#abbeysautism

text: What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: “I’m not a zoomer-arounder like you…” The truth comes out. Some days, you just want to lay around all day. I get it. Life with a zoomer-arounder mama and papa can be tough!  Truth is, Emi is a bit of a zoomer too—but she knows when she needs her downtime. Like me, she needs that balance of also being a ‘layer-arounder.’ I’m glad she can tell me when she feels that way and knows I’ll support her.✨ This conversation went on for at least 5 more minutes as Emi and I skied together last spring. I listened, following up on her thoughts to better understand what she was expressing and feeling. I learned a lot. She revealed that if she has her way, she’d snuggle with her Squishmallows all day, only getting up to brush her teeth—so, there’s that. But I sensed there was more to it knowing she’s the kiddo usually begging to go skiing or sprint down the trail in a hike. ⬇️ This was newly-5-year-old Emi’s first time skiing off the very top of Mount Bachelor. It was steep, the snow was firm, and I could hear the hesitation in her voice. So, we took a break right after this exchange. I realized she was too hot, so I peeled off one of her layers, reminded her, “I got you,” and told her I had the slope rope to connect us if she wanted it. Once we made it past the steep section, hit some softer snow, and ate some gummies, she zoomed off ahead of me, and I couldn’t keep up!  As ski season arrives, it’s a good reminder for us parents to check in with the deeper story to what’s going on when we’re out on the mountain with our kids.  @Milo @Stio Outdoor Apparel @mt.bachelor @Reima @ikonpass  #winteriscoming #zoomerarounder #skiingwithkids #girlswhoski #skigirl #outdoormom

text: Our relationship and marriage have been far from picture perfect. I keep seeing posts saying “if marriage is hard, you probably married the wrong person” but I don’t believe that’s true. Especially not for the believer. I’ll always believe that kingdom-enhancing marriages are one of the enemy’s number one targets. If your marriage has the power to reflect Christ’s love, to serve others, to raise disciples, of course it’ll face attack. Marriage is meant to be sanctifying. It’s meant to make us holy, not just happy. Do I believe God desires harmony in marriage? Absolutely. But Garrett and I started dating at 18… and we were messy, messy humans. We still are. Now we’re just messy humans who’ve walked with Jesus seven years longer. Messy humans who’ve been discipled, who’ve met the Holy Spirit, who’ve gone to counseling, who’ve grown and matured and learned how to love more selflessly and sacrificially. Our marriage was never meant to be the source of our fulfillment. Garrett’s job isn’t to fill my soul. Should he pursue my heart? Yes. But should I depend on him to complete me? Absolutely not. And vice versa. It’s not my job to complete Garrett either. We’ve screamed. We’ve fought. We even had the cops called on us in the first three months of marriage because of how loud we were arguing. Not proud, just keeping it real. But the Lord has called us into union, and He’s faithful to finish what He started. So to the young married couple stuck in the trenches, figuring each other out while also figuring yourself out, your marriage isn’t broken. You didn’t choose wrong. God didn’t mess up. Keep seeking the cross. Die to yourself. Admit when you’re wrong. Invite community in. Get the help you need. Pray for your spouse more than you complain about them to your friends. Pray for your spouse more than you nag them. Test God on it. Pray, pray, pray fervently for your spouse and your marriage. Watch Him move. And please hear me. What’s left when your hands forget how to make? Deep in the gnarled spine of northern Romania, where the air smells of fir resin and time is measured by the rhythm of tools on timber, old men still coax life out of wood with nothing but a blade, their knees, and a prayer. It’s not for beauty—they’ll tell you, chuckling like men who’ve danced with storms—it’s for the roof over your head, the roof over God’s head. Each shingle, split with monk-like patience, shaped with a knife kissed by callus and conviction, is a sliver of soul offered to shelter. This is a craft born not from manuals, but from watching your grandfather’s knuckles bleed in the frost, from understanding how a linden plank yields only when spoken to with reverence. The knife—held in two hands like a communion chalice—doesn’t just slice; it converses with the grain, persuades, seduces. Every motion a negotiation with nature, every curl of wood a verse of an unwritten poem. Machines could do it faster, yes. But this? This is about rhythm, not result. It’s about loving your labor so fiercely, so irrationally, that you’d rather grow old with it than get rich without it. What do we lose when we stop making things with our hands? When our roofs are no longer born from sweat but from sterile factories? In these shingles lie secrets and sorrow, storm-warnings and lullabies. They don’t just protect—they witness. Who taught us to worship efficiency over essence? And when did we forget that the soul, too, is carved with a blade and shaped with both hands? text: Trump Gets His Tariff Power Taken Away #usa #america  The US Court of International Trade has unanimously ruled that Trump doesn’t have tariff authority so his liberation day tariffs have been ruled to be illegal and are now permanently blocked unless he gets an emergency stay. They also blocked the fentanyl tariffs on Mexico, Canada, and China from earlier this year, when we were all 9 years younger. And folks the market is absolutely exploding. So the court says that Trump doesn’t have the legal authority to declare a national emergency, that tariff power solely resides with Congress and that Trump violated the constitution, and that the law he cited to do this doesn’t give him the authority to do tariffs. This lawsuit was brought by several states and several companies including a wine seller. They argued that the law Trump cited to do this doesn’t even mention tariffs and that he was imposing taxes on Americans without their consent. So while almost all of the tariffs are done and blocked for now. The tariffs on cars, car parts, and steel and aluminum are still in play because Trump used a different law for that. The futures market is exploding. The dollar is increasing in value, other currencies are currently falling just as fast. Legal experts say that the court decision has him dead to rights, and that he actually doesn’t have the authority in any universe to do this. But some lawyers say, well maybe they just need to use a different law. But Trump is now appealing because tariffs are his favorite thing. Unless he gets an emergency stay on this ruling, the tariffs are over for now. People are split though. Some say, this is the perfect offramp for the White House, they can just let the whole tariff episode fade into the background and take credit for the economy. But others say, yeah maybe it’s perfect for the White House and Republicans but not for Trump so that’s why they’re appealing.

text: “I’m not a zoomer-arounder like you…” The truth comes out. Some days, you just want to lay around all day. I get it. Life with a zoomer-arounder mama and papa can be tough!  Truth is, Emi is a bit of a zoomer too—but she knows when she needs her downtime. Like me, she needs that balance of also being a ‘layer-arounder.’ I’m glad she can tell me when she feels that way and knows I’ll support her.✨ This conversation went on for at least 5 more minutes as Emi and I skied together last spring. I listened, following up on her thoughts to better understand what she was expressing and feeling. I learned a lot. She revealed that if she has her way, she’d snuggle with her Squishmallows all day, only getting up to brush her teeth—so, there’s that. But I sensed there was more to it knowing she’s the kiddo usually begging to go skiing or sprint down the trail in a hike. ⬇️ This was newly-5-year-old Emi’s first time skiing off the very top of Mount Bachelor. It was steep, the snow was firm, and I could hear the hesitation in her voice. So, we took a break right after this exchange. I realized she was too hot, so I peeled off one of her layers, reminded her, “I got you,” and told her I had the slope rope to connect us if she wanted it. Once we made it past the steep section, hit some softer snow, and ate some gummies, she zoomed off ahead of me, and I couldn’t keep up!  As ski season arrives, it’s a good reminder for us parents to check in with the deeper story to what’s going on when we’re out on the mountain with our kids.  @Milo @Stio Outdoor Apparel @mt.bachelor @Reima @ikonpass  #winteriscoming #zoomerarounder #skiingwithkids #girlswhoski #skigirl #outdoormom
